%U A395740 5,5,9,2,6,7,2,7,2,3,7,6,5,4,7,12,2,4,2
%N A395740 Number of iterations for the n-th prime to reach 2 under the function f(p) = smallest odd prime factor of 3*p+1 or 2 if 3*p+1 is a power of 2.
%C A395740 All primes eventually reach 2.
%H A395740 J. O. del Toro Barroso, <a href="https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18796390">Una función iterativa sobre números primos que siempre termina en 2</a> (An iterative function on prime numbers that always ends in 2), Zenodo, 2026.
%e A395740 a(4) = 5 because the fourth prime, 7, follows the trajectory 7 -> 11 -> 17 -> 13 -> 5 -> 2, taking 5 steps.
%o A395740 (PARI) oddp(n) = n/2^valuation(n,2); \\ A078701
%o A395740 a(n) = my(p=prime(n), nb=0); while(p!=2, nb++; p=oddp(3*p+1); if (p==1, p=2, p=factor(p)[1,1])); nb; \\ _Michel Marcus_, May 06 2026
%Y A395740 Cf. A078701.
%K A395740 nonn,new
%O A395740 1,2
%A A395740 _Jose O. del Toro Barroso_, May 05 2026
%E A395740 More terms from _Alois P. Heinz_, May 05 2026
